        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We want to map the CO(3-2) line (and simultaneously HCO+(4-3) in a rectangle centered on the nucleus and covering the whole optical polar ring. This corresponds to a 38_point mosaic. To benefit from high spatial resolution, we require the extended configuration in Band 7, with 0.16” of resolution. 
We will observe in dual polarization mode with 1.875 GHz total bandwidth per baseband, and velocity resolution of 4MHz ~ 3.5 km/s (FDM). When this velocity resolution is too high, we will smooth the spectra to 10km/s in CO(2-2), and even to higher velocity in the HCO+ line.

The CO(2-1) profile obtained with the CSO 36” beam towards the Southern part of the disk (Watson et al. 1994) yields a Tmb peak temperature of 42mK, with a FWHM velocity width of 170km/s (cf Table 1). This is equivalent to a peak flux of 1.85Jy. This integrated signal of 314 Jy.Km/s might be distributed in 1000 GMC of 7105 Mo in average, of 30mJy and 10km/s, with 30pc size (our resolution). In CO(3-2) the flux is likely to be twice higher. We therefore require an rms of 2mJy to be able to reach an S/N=15. This is a conservative limit, since it is likely that some GMC will add their signal in projection, the polar disk being almost edge-on.
Given the very contrasted structure found in the HST image of star forming knots, we do not expect a diffuse emission of molecular gas. With 30pc resolution, we expect instead to detect the clumpy structure of GMC ad Giant associations, dispersed in velocity due to the edge-on projection. We therefore do not require the ACA. According to the actual density of clouds, we might detect directly HCO+(4-3) in some positions. If not, we will be able to stack the emission with the right velocity, when detected in CO(3-2), to get a global relative intensity with respect to the CO.

The wide bandwidths (LSB and USB) of the ALMA correlator will also be used to map the continuum emission of the dust (this time with TDM). The upper limit at 100m obtained with IRAS is only 1.5 Jy.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
